---
import NoteLayout from '../../layouts/NoteLayout.astro';
---

<NoteLayout 
  title="Sample Note" 
  date={new Date('2024-01-15')}
  tags={['example', 'demo']}
>
  <p>This is a comprehensive sample note demonstrating the note layout with table of contents on the right side. Notes are designed for quick reference articles and one-pagers that you want to access quickly.</p>

  <h2>Introduction</h2>
  <p>Notes are single-page articles with a table of contents on the right side. They're perfect for documenting quick tips, reference materials, or standalone concepts that don't require multiple chapters.</p>
  
  <p>The layout automatically generates a table of contents from your h2 and h3 headings, making it easy to navigate longer articles. The TOC is sticky, so it stays visible as you scroll through the content.</p>

  <h2>Key Features</h2>
  <p>The note layout includes several features designed to enhance readability and sharing:</p>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Automatic table of contents generation</strong> - No manual work needed, just write your headings</li>
    <li><strong>Share buttons for social media</strong> - LinkedIn and X (Twitter) integration</li>
    <li><strong>Responsive design</strong> - Works beautifully on desktop, tablet, and mobile</li>
    <li><strong>Clean typography</strong> - Optimized for technical content with proper code formatting</li>
    <li><strong>Comment system</strong> - Giscus integration for discussions</li>
  </ul>

  <h3>Typography and Readability</h3>
  <p>The content width is optimized at 720px maximum, which provides approximately 66-75 characters per line - the ideal range for comfortable reading. This is based on research showing that line lengths in this range reduce eye strain and improve comprehension.</p>

  <p>Text uses a softer gray color (#c9d1d9) instead of pure white, which is easier on the eyes during extended reading sessions. Headings use a brighter white (#e6edf3) to create clear visual hierarchy.</p>

  <h3>Code Examples</h3>
  <p>Code blocks are styled with proper syntax highlighting support. Here's an inline code example: <code>const example = 'value';</code></p>

  <p>Block code examples maintain readability with appropriate spacing and contrast.</p>

  <h2>Content Organization</h2>
  <p>When writing notes, consider organizing your content with clear sections. Use h2 for main sections and h3 for subsections. This creates a logical hierarchy that's reflected in the table of contents.</p>

  <h3>Best Practices</h3>
  <p>Here are some tips for writing effective notes:</p>
  <ol>
    <li>Start with a clear introduction that explains what the note covers</li>
    <li>Use descriptive headings that make sense out of context</li>
    <li>Keep paragraphs focused on a single idea</li>
    <li>Use lists to break down complex information</li>
    <li>Include code examples where relevant</li>
  </ol>

  <h3>Visual Elements</h3>
  <p>You can include various visual elements to enhance your notes. Images, tables, and blockquotes all have appropriate styling.</p>

  <blockquote>
    <p>This is a blockquote. Use it for important callouts, quotes, or highlighting key information that deserves special attention.</p>
  </blockquote>

  <h2>Sharing and Collaboration</h2>
  <p>Each note includes share buttons at the bottom, making it easy to share your content on LinkedIn and X. The Giscus comment system allows readers to leave feedback and start discussions directly on the page.</p>

  <h2>Conclusion</h2>
  <p>This layout is perfect for quick reference articles and one-pagers. The combination of clean typography, optimal reading width, and helpful navigation features creates an excellent reading experience for technical content.</p>
  
  <p>Try scrolling through this page and notice how the table of contents on the right helps you navigate. On mobile devices, the TOC is hidden to maximize content space, but the content remains perfectly readable.</p>
</NoteLayout>
